      '"Why is your minimum 300 kg? That is far more pouches than I need for my launch." This is one of the most common questions we get from first-time packaging buyers. The short answer is that 300 kg is the smallest run where the economics still work for both sides — for us as the manufacturer and for the brand as the customer. The longer answer involves plate amortisation, machine setup time, and material waste, and it is worth understanding before you compare quotes from different suppliers.',
      '## What MOQ actually measures',
      'MOQ in flexible packaging is **kilograms of laminated film per SKU per design**. Not pieces, not metres, not orders — kilograms of finished laminate that comes off the line. Each unique artwork is a separate SKU. A brand with three pack sizes (1 kg, 5 kg, 10 kg) and one common artwork still has three SKUs because each pack size is engineered differently.',
      'For a 1 kg atta pouch, 300 kg of laminate translates to roughly 270 finished pouches after about 10% conversion waste during printing and slitting. For a 5 kg pouch, the same 300 kg gives you 54 pouches.',
      '## Why MOQ exists — three reasons',
      '**1. Plate amortisation.** Rotogravure printing uses engraved metal cylinders, one per colour. An 8-colour design needs 8 cylinders, each costing a few thousand rupees to engrave. The plates are a fixed cost paid once per design. At a 100 kg run, plate cost adds meaningfully to the per-pouch price; at 1,000 kg, plate cost is small per pouch. Below 300 kg, the per-pouch price gets uncomfortable for buyers — especially when they realise plates are still theirs to reorder against.',
      '**2. Machine setup time.** Setting up a rotogravure press for a new design takes 2-4 hours — mounting cylinders, dialling in ink colours, registering colour positions, running test sheets, getting customer sign-off. That setup time is the same whether the run is 100 kg or 5,000 kg. Below 300 kg, setup time becomes the dominant cost.',
      '**3. Material waste.** First metres off the press are calibration runs — colour does not register cleanly until 50-100 metres in. This material is discarded. At 100 kg total run, calibration waste is a large proportion. At 300 kg+, it is a small proportion.',
